<[TST]Bot> -!- Taiyaki|たい焼き|, literally "baked sea bream" is a Japanese fish-shaped cake. The most common filling is red bean paste that is made from sweetened azuki beans. Other common fillings may be custard, chocolate, or cheese. Some shops even sell taiyaki with okonomiyaki, gyoza filling, or a sausage inside.

<nickstr> a codec is a piece of hardware or software that encodes and decodes audio or video information
<nickstr> a container is what ties the audio and video information along with other things like subtitles together in a single digital file or stream
<junh1024-XD> so saying "I HAVE A MOV THAT WONT OPEN!!!" isn't very informative at all. You have specified the container [mov], but not the compression schemes inside it [h264,sorenson] for video, or [aiff,ima,aac] for video.
<junh1024-XD> which is what really matters.
<nickstr> plus you can find some oddball codecs used in some containers
<nickstr> for example I have seen Windows Media Video in the AVI container
<junh1024-XD> containers [avi,mov,mp4] CONTAIN codecs which use compression schemes [xvid,h264,sorenson] , to store stuff. those are only a few examples. so do you get it now?
<SilverSonic|Upset> hmm..
<SilverSonic|Upset> _help help
<SilverSonic|Upset> darn
<junh1024-XD> you may be able to change codec independent of container using some tools, and vice-versa,
<nickstr> a process known as demuxing
<nickstr> splitting the streams within a container into individual files or streams
